{
  "ruleId": "ProtectedMemberInFinalClass",
  "description": "Reports 'protected' members in 'final' classes with no 'protected' modifier. Since 'final' classes cannot be inherited, marking the method as 'protected' may be confusing. It is better to declare such members as 'private' or package-visible instead. Example: 'record Bar(int a, int b) {\n  protected int sum() { \n     return a + b;\n  }\n}'\n After the quick-fix is applied: 'record Bar(int a, int b) {\n  int sum() { \n     return a + b;\n  }\n}' As shown in the example, a class can be marked as 'final' explicitly or implicitly. Inspection ID: ProtectedMemberInFinalClass",
  "positiveExamples": [
    {
